WEBVTT

00:01.460 --> 00:04.878
[dramatic music]

00:04.922 --> 00:06.922
(Wil Willis voice-over)
Since the dawn
of human civilization,

00:06.966 --> 00:10.634
mankind has made weapons.

00:10.678 --> 00:13.345
What began with sharpening
sticks and pounding stone

00:13.389 --> 00:15.806
has evolved
into a highly complex skill

00:15.850 --> 00:19.893
requiring the taming of fire
and steel.

00:19.937 --> 00:21.812
Whoa!

00:21.856 --> 00:23.647
(Wil voice-over)
The secrets and traditions
of weapon making

00:23.691 --> 00:25.941
have been kept alive by
an elite group of bladesmiths...

00:25.985 --> 00:27.818
Heat up, heat up, heat up.

00:27.862 --> 00:29.653
(Wil voice-over)
Who have honed and perfected
their skills

00:29.697 --> 00:32.489
over thousands of years.

00:32.533 --> 00:33.657
[fire whooshes]

00:33.701 --> 00:35.534
Now for the first time ever,

00:35.578 --> 00:37.494
these men will go head-to-head

00:37.538 --> 00:39.872
and put their skills
to the ultimate test.

00:39.915 --> 00:41.832
Welcome to the Forge.

00:41.876 --> 00:43.876
It starts with a lump
of raw steel

00:43.919 --> 00:45.669
and a ticking clock...

00:45.713 --> 00:47.838
Damn near impossible to
forge your blade in that time.

00:47.882 --> 00:49.256
(Wil voice-over)
And by the end of two rounds,

00:49.300 --> 00:51.341
the bladesmiths must present
a weapon

00:51.385 --> 00:54.678
capable of cutting, chopping,
and slicing.

00:54.722 --> 00:56.847
If the blades they create
don't make the grade,

00:56.891 --> 00:58.390
they are eliminated.

00:58.434 --> 00:59.683
[shouts]

00:59.727 --> 01:01.018
(Wil voice-over)
The top two craftsmen

01:01.062 --> 01:02.728
then move on to
the final challenge,

01:02.772 --> 01:05.606
where they must create
one of the most iconic weapons

01:05.649 --> 01:07.024
ever made by man.

01:07.068 --> 01:08.650
From the Japanese katana

01:08.694 --> 01:10.069
to the Viking battle axe,

01:10.112 --> 01:12.237
each has its own unique history

01:12.281 --> 01:14.198
as told
through the forging process.

01:14.241 --> 01:16.200
I cut my finger open.

01:16.243 --> 01:18.077
(Wil voice-over)
The contestants' weapons must be
works of art

01:18.120 --> 01:20.287
as well as deadly instruments
of war,

01:20.331 --> 01:23.624
and they must survive a battery
of explosive tests,

01:23.667 --> 01:27.044
as well as the scrutiny
of an expert panel of judges.

01:27.088 --> 01:29.254
In the end,
there can be only one,

01:29.298 --> 01:31.715
and he will take home $10,000

01:31.759 --> 01:35.594
and be crowned
a<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

01:35.638 --> 01:38.597
[dramatic music]

01:38.641 --> 01:41.391
♪ ♪

01:41.435 --> 01:44.436
[heavy metal music]

01:44.480 --> 01:46.605
♪ ♪

01:46.649 --> 01:48.148
(Joe)
My name is Joe Waits.

01:48.192 --> 01:49.900
I'm the head blade maker
at one of the largest

01:49.944 --> 01:51.777
distributors of swords
in the world.

01:51.821 --> 01:53.070
(Rich)
My name is Rich Greenwood.

01:53.114 --> 01:54.571
By day, I work on
swimming pools,

01:54.615 --> 01:56.281
and at night I'm a bladesmith.

01:56.325 --> 01:57.741
(Matthew)
My name is Matthew Parkinson.

01:57.785 --> 02:00.244
I've been a blacksmith
for 15 years.

02:00.287 --> 02:01.829
(Billy)
I'm Billy Hilton.

02:01.872 --> 02:05.749
I'm a self-taught blacksmith
and bladesmith.

02:05.793 --> 02:09.128
Welcome, and congratulations
on making it to the Forge.

02:09.171 --> 02:12.756
(Billy)
Getting our first glimpse into
the forging area is amazing.

02:12.800 --> 02:14.967
Everything's picture-perfect.

02:15.010 --> 02:18.137
(Wil)
Between you, the title
of<i> Forged In Fire</i> champion,

02:18.180 --> 02:19.972
and a check for $10,000

02:20.015 --> 02:23.642
are three extremely
difficult challenges

02:23.686 --> 02:25.978
designed to put your
weapon-making skills

02:26.021 --> 02:27.938
to the test.

02:27.982 --> 02:30.899
After each round, you will give
your work to the judges.

02:30.943 --> 02:34.111
They will decide who stays
and who goes.

02:34.155 --> 02:36.280
Two of you will advance
to a final,

02:36.323 --> 02:38.782
where you will forge
one of the greatest weapons

02:38.826 --> 02:41.451
ever made by mankind.

02:41.495 --> 02:43.787
Now it's time to meet
our judges.

02:43.831 --> 02:46.290
First up,
solo weapons-making expert

02:46.333 --> 02:50.169
and internationally known
master bladesmith J. Neilson.

02:50.212 --> 02:52.296
Next, world-renowned swordsmith

02:52.339 --> 02:55.716
and rare weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker.

02:55.759 --> 02:57.718
And finally
edged weapons specialist

02:57.761 --> 03:01.013
and martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

03:01.056 --> 03:02.472
It's time to get to work.

03:02.516 --> 03:05.601
In front of you on your anvil
is a cloth.

03:05.644 --> 03:09.980
Go ahead and lift that up.

03:10.024 --> 03:12.482
That is a bar
of high-carbon steel.

03:12.526 --> 03:14.359
From that lump of raw metal,

03:14.403 --> 03:18.155
you must design and forge
a fully functioning weapon.

03:18.199 --> 03:21.283
The blade itself should be
in your own style.

03:21.327 --> 03:23.911
You have ten minutes to work
on your design

03:23.954 --> 03:26.496
and three hours to forge
your blade.

03:26.540 --> 03:29.166
(Rich)
Normally, it takes me three days
to make a knife.

03:29.210 --> 03:31.001
I don't know how
I'm gonna pull it off.

03:31.045 --> 03:34.713
The blade must fall within
the following size parameters.

03:34.757 --> 03:37.507
The length of the blade
should be at least 9 inches

03:37.551 --> 03:39.968
but not more than 11 inches.

03:40.012 --> 03:41.720
And just to spice things up
a little bit,

03:41.764 --> 03:45.015
you must also include
a serrated edge into that blade.

03:45.059 --> 03:49.353
The length of the serration
should be at least 4 inches.

03:49.396 --> 03:51.188
(Matthew)
I've done some serrations
in the past,

03:51.232 --> 03:53.690
but it's much more stressful
in this situation.

03:53.734 --> 03:55.359
(Wil)
After three hours,

03:55.402 --> 03:57.569
one of you will be asked
to surrender your weapon

03:57.613 --> 03:59.238
and go home.

03:59.281 --> 04:00.822
Good luck, gentlemen.

04:00.866 --> 04:03.867
Your ten-minute design window
begins now.

04:03.911 --> 04:07.246
[fast-paced music]

04:07.289 --> 04:10.540
I specialize in doing a lot
of historical work.

04:10.584 --> 04:12.542
I'm basing this knife
off of Continental Seax.

04:12.586 --> 04:14.044
It's a German war knife.

04:14.088 --> 04:15.921
Historical stuff always
fascinates me,

04:15.965 --> 04:18.715
'cause it's like being able
to pull this idea of history

04:18.759 --> 04:20.926
into the modern age.

04:20.970 --> 04:24.221
(Billy)
I specialize in practical,
everyday knives,

04:24.265 --> 04:27.224
so my design
is a drop-point bowie.

04:27.268 --> 04:28.934
It's typically a camp knife.

04:28.978 --> 04:30.602
It's for everyday chores.

04:30.646 --> 04:32.020
It'll chop a tree down

04:32.064 --> 04:33.563
and still be able
to cut your apple

04:33.607 --> 04:35.565
when you're ready for dinner.

04:35.609 --> 04:38.902
My inspiration comes from
Japanese blade making.

04:38.946 --> 04:40.112
I'm going with a Tanto blade,

04:40.155 --> 04:42.239
because it fits the style
of knife

04:42.283 --> 04:43.407
that I enjoy making--

04:43.450 --> 04:45.742
hunting, fighting-style knives.

04:45.786 --> 04:47.953
I grew up with a family
of craftsmen

04:47.997 --> 04:49.288
and blue-collar workers.

04:49.331 --> 04:51.123
I think that just gave me
the ability

04:51.166 --> 04:54.251
to not worry about getting
my hands dirty.

04:54.295 --> 04:56.837
My interest in swords began
at an early age

04:56.880 --> 04:58.755
after seeing
<i> Conan The Barbarian.</i>

04:58.799 --> 05:00.465
It's one of
the most iconic movies

05:00.509 --> 05:02.509
and has one of
the most iconic swords.

05:02.553 --> 05:04.094
I'm gonna make a bowie.

05:04.138 --> 05:05.679
It's a classic design,
clip point.

05:05.723 --> 05:07.764
It'll stab right through
whatever they test.

05:07.808 --> 05:09.766
If some great character
like Conan had it,

05:09.810 --> 05:11.476
I think he would feel
comfortable

05:11.520 --> 05:14.938
cutting a giant snake's head off
with it.

05:14.982 --> 05:16.940
(Wil)
Bladesmiths, your ten-minute
design window

05:16.984 --> 05:18.317
is closed.

05:18.360 --> 05:20.944
You may start forging
your blades now!

05:20.988 --> 05:25.157
[rock music]

05:25.200 --> 05:26.950
(Matt)
The clock starts.

05:26.994 --> 05:28.785
I toss my bar into the forge
as soon as the bar's hot,

05:28.829 --> 05:30.829
and then I knocked the bar down
a little bit.

05:30.873 --> 05:32.664
The actual definition of forging

05:32.708 --> 05:35.792
is when you use the plastic
state of metal to deform it,

05:35.836 --> 05:38.420
using blows from a hammer
or pressure from a press

05:38.464 --> 05:40.297
for it to be where I want
and need it to be

05:40.341 --> 05:42.174
for whatever shape
I'm trying to make.

05:42.217 --> 05:43.550
(Billy)
So you ever cooked your beard?

05:43.594 --> 05:44.718
(Matt)
A couple times.

05:44.762 --> 05:46.136
It never gets longer
than this,

05:46.180 --> 05:47.804
'cause I'm always
burning it back.

05:47.848 --> 05:49.431
I try not to shave,

05:49.475 --> 05:50.640
'cause I look like
a perverted Boy Scout.

05:50.684 --> 05:52.309
[laughs]

05:52.353 --> 05:53.685
(Billy)
My strategy for this competition

05:53.729 --> 05:55.854
is to simply get 'er done.

05:55.898 --> 05:57.689
I'm forging right now,

05:57.733 --> 05:59.691
trying to get a little bit
of swag in it,

05:59.735 --> 06:02.152
trying to make it look
a little bit purdy.

06:02.196 --> 06:04.321
What I'm going to do with this
prize money when I win is,

06:04.365 --> 06:06.073
I'm gonna build a bigger shop.

06:06.116 --> 06:07.407
My wife does engraving.

06:07.451 --> 06:08.992
I do knife making.

06:09.036 --> 06:11.828
We're combining the two
into one comfy shop.

06:11.872 --> 06:13.413
Oh, yeah.

06:13.457 --> 06:15.791
♪ ♪

06:15.834 --> 06:17.626
(J.)
Joe's chugging right along.

06:17.669 --> 06:19.336
(Joe)
My main goal
in this competition

06:19.380 --> 06:22.672
is to crush my enemies,
to see them driven before me,

06:22.716 --> 06:24.674
and to hear the lamentations
of their women.

06:26.553 --> 06:27.844
Everything's going
according to plan,

06:27.888 --> 06:29.513
which is slow and easy.

06:29.556 --> 06:30.847
He's being very meticulous.

06:30.891 --> 06:32.349
(Wil)
He may be the kind of guy

06:32.393 --> 06:33.725
that he figures he's got
three hours.

06:33.769 --> 06:35.060
He can do a work of art.

06:35.104 --> 06:36.686
Yeah?
We'll see what happens.

06:36.730 --> 06:38.855
Coming behind you with
a hot piece of steel.

06:38.899 --> 06:41.191
During my career, I've made
over 6,000 blades,

06:41.235 --> 06:42.984
and I do not believe
that anybody else

06:43.028 --> 06:45.195
can even approach that number
in this competition.

06:45.239 --> 06:47.197
(David)
It seems that Joe's doing
some thermocycling.

06:47.241 --> 06:48.698
He's brought it up.

06:48.742 --> 06:50.200
He's let it cool
a couple of times now.

06:52.079 --> 06:55.038
(Wil)
He's still got that forge going
full-bore.

06:55.082 --> 06:56.873
You don't want to keep
overheating that tip.

06:56.917 --> 06:58.708
(Wil)
What happens if you burn
the steel?

06:58.752 --> 07:00.752
You're gonna weaken
the structure of the steel.

07:00.796 --> 07:03.797
[pounding and thudding]

07:07.261 --> 07:10.762
(Rich)
As I'm watching everybody
bang on their steel and forge

07:10.806 --> 07:13.056
and mine's still heating up,
I'm thinking,

07:13.100 --> 07:16.393
"I may have chosen just
a little too large of blade."

07:16.437 --> 07:18.228
I'm really kind of worried
about Rich.

07:18.272 --> 07:19.896
I'm starting to fall behind.

07:19.940 --> 07:21.565
Am I the only one
that's sweating or what?

07:21.608 --> 07:22.899
(Wil)
Gentlemen!

07:22.943 --> 07:24.985
You have 90 minutes remaining!

07:25.028 --> 07:30.407
♪ ♪

07:30.451 --> 07:33.034
(J.)
He's putting on his bandolier
of belts.

07:33.078 --> 07:37.038
(Billy)
I start getting my geometry
correct on my blade

07:37.082 --> 07:38.707
to make sure everything
is perpendicular, in line.

07:38.750 --> 07:40.792
This is what you call
getting up close and personal,

07:40.836 --> 07:42.502
getting your spark on.

07:42.546 --> 07:44.337
(David)
Look at those sparks
coming off of that.

07:44.381 --> 07:47.549
(Billy)
♪ Getting hot up in here
tonight ♪

07:47.593 --> 07:50.260
♪ ♪

07:50.304 --> 07:52.095
Matt has definitely
jumped ahead.

07:52.139 --> 07:54.264
He's already got a tip
worked out on that sucker.

07:54.308 --> 07:56.266
I got a good amount
of time left.

07:56.310 --> 07:58.602
I'm basically there.
It's all finish work now.

07:58.645 --> 07:59.603
My grandfather was a welder,

07:59.646 --> 08:01.021
and his level of metal working

08:01.064 --> 08:03.440
kind of influenced me
as a child.

08:03.484 --> 08:04.941
I actually named my son
after him.

08:04.985 --> 08:06.318
I'm gonna win this for my son.

08:06.361 --> 08:07.944
I'm gonna win this
for my grandfather.

08:07.988 --> 08:10.280
Once this is down to, like,
almost touchable,

08:10.324 --> 08:12.282
I quench it in water
just so I can handle it

08:12.326 --> 08:14.159
and start filing
the serrations in.

08:14.203 --> 08:16.161
Matt just went in
for a quench.

08:16.205 --> 08:17.287
(J.)
Oh!

08:17.331 --> 08:18.830
He's got some heat on there yet.

08:23.504 --> 08:25.962
I'm still trying to figure out
what Rich is trying to do.

08:26.006 --> 08:28.131
(J.)
I don't think Rich is
comfortable with his pace.

08:28.175 --> 08:32.719
Proving a little more difficult
that I thought it'd be.

08:32.763 --> 08:34.513
I'm looking around,
and I'm seeing progress

08:34.556 --> 08:36.765
that the other contestants
are making.

08:36.808 --> 08:37.807
How's it going?

08:37.851 --> 08:39.142
Kind of close to done.

08:39.186 --> 08:41.895
It's kind of making me panic.
[bleep].

08:41.939 --> 08:43.021
(Wil)
Man, we got a blade
on the floor.

08:43.065 --> 08:44.689
I'm very concerned.

08:44.733 --> 08:46.149
(David)
The more tired and frustrated
you get,

08:46.193 --> 08:48.193
the more drops
you'll wind up with.

08:48.237 --> 08:50.654
And it's like trying
to pick up a dime

08:50.697 --> 08:51.655
without fingernails.

08:51.698 --> 08:54.699
[banging]

08:54.743 --> 08:56.159
[inaudible]

08:56.203 --> 08:59.996
I think I may bit off more
than I can chew.

09:00.040 --> 09:01.498
(Matt)
Part of the requirement was that

09:01.542 --> 09:02.999
it had to be at least 4 inches
of serration,

09:03.043 --> 09:05.168
so I drew the serrations
in a 4 1/2 inch section

09:05.212 --> 09:06.378
just to make sure
I had a little extra

09:06.421 --> 09:09.214
and not just 4 exactly.

09:09.258 --> 09:11.758
(Wil)
Doug, what difference does
a serrated edge make

09:11.802 --> 09:13.051
to combat?

09:13.095 --> 09:14.177
(Doug)
You don't have to time

09:14.221 --> 09:15.679
to keep sharpening your blade.

09:15.722 --> 09:17.556
Having that option gives you
the function to cut

09:17.599 --> 09:20.141
without having to constantly
keep your blade sharp.

09:22.312 --> 09:23.353
[laughs]

09:23.397 --> 09:24.521
One hour, gentlemen!

09:24.565 --> 09:26.773
You have one hour remaining!

09:26.817 --> 09:27.983
Holy crap!

09:28.026 --> 09:30.694
♪ ♪

09:30.737 --> 09:32.445
Right now, it's starting
to feel alive.

09:32.489 --> 09:33.905
The blade's starting to move
like it should.

09:33.949 --> 09:35.699
For a fighting knife,
it's got to move,

09:35.742 --> 09:38.326
and it's really starting.

09:38.370 --> 09:41.538
♪ ♪

09:41.582 --> 09:43.206
Oh, [bleep].

09:43.250 --> 09:44.624
(David)
Oh, no.

09:44.668 --> 09:46.042
- Uh-oh.
- Oh, no.

09:46.086 --> 09:47.085
Ah, come on.

09:47.129 --> 09:48.878
(J.)
He just broke the blade.

09:48.922 --> 09:50.755
He just lost an inch
off the tip of his blade.

09:50.799 --> 09:52.257
(J.)
Joe's blade broke.

09:52.301 --> 09:53.550
(David)
Just when you think you're done,

09:53.594 --> 09:55.427
always something else pops up.

09:55.470 --> 09:57.387
(Joe)
I think I overshot my
temperature a little bit,

09:57.431 --> 09:59.306
overhardened the tip
of my blade,

09:59.349 --> 10:00.557
and it broke off.

10:00.601 --> 10:02.017
[sighs]

10:02.060 --> 10:03.560
(David)
I'm hoping he makes the length.

10:03.604 --> 10:04.603
I'm hoping he didn't drop below.

10:04.646 --> 10:06.062
9 to 11 inches,

10:06.106 --> 10:08.148
and maybe 1 1/2 inches
of that thing came off.

10:08.191 --> 10:10.817
I'm coming in short,
so it is over.

10:10.861 --> 10:12.444
[groans]

10:12.487 --> 10:14.446
I believe I've just lost
the entire thing.

10:16.116 --> 10:17.907
- Can't quit.
- Don't quit.

10:17.951 --> 10:18.992
(David)
Please.

10:24.625 --> 10:26.958
[heavy metal music]

10:27.002 --> 10:28.251
(Wil)
One hour, gentlemen!

10:28.295 --> 10:29.919
One hour remaining!

10:29.963 --> 10:31.755
The blade's starting to move
like it should.

10:31.798 --> 10:36.134
(Wil)
Joe's chugging right along.

10:36.178 --> 10:38.595
- Oh, no.
- That's heartbreaking.

10:38.639 --> 10:40.430
(Joe)
The tip broke off of my blade,

10:40.474 --> 10:42.223
and I don't see a way
to recover from this.

10:42.267 --> 10:43.808
(David)
I'm hoping he makes the length.

10:43.852 --> 10:45.060
I'm hoping he didn't drop below.

10:45.103 --> 10:46.603
9 to 11 inches,

10:46.647 --> 10:48.730
and maybe 1 1/2 inches
of that thing came off.

10:48.774 --> 10:50.482
Fate.

10:50.525 --> 10:52.150
If you can't see a pathway
forward,

10:52.194 --> 10:54.277
sometimes the best way
is to get out,

10:54.321 --> 10:56.029
and I just had to leave.

10:57.574 --> 10:58.531
(David)
Don't quit.

10:58.575 --> 10:59.491
- Hey, Joe.
- Yeah.

10:59.534 --> 11:01.117
You can still finish that blade.

11:01.161 --> 11:02.827
You can just grind it down.

11:02.871 --> 11:04.621
It might be able to make it
into the final challenge.

11:04.665 --> 11:06.331
Go for it, man.

11:06.375 --> 11:08.124
Just do what you can with
the time you have left.

11:08.168 --> 11:10.085
Don't walk out on it;
you've worked too hard.

11:10.128 --> 11:11.961
He made a point.

11:12.005 --> 11:14.130
I wouldn't have the elegant look
I was going for,

11:14.174 --> 11:16.549
but I could have a reformed tip
on the grinder.

11:16.593 --> 11:18.301
(Wil)
He could still pull it off.

11:18.345 --> 11:19.928
As long as he's still got
9 inches of blade there,

11:19.971 --> 11:20.929
he's good to go.

11:20.972 --> 11:24.140
♪ ♪

11:24.184 --> 11:26.559
(David)
Look at the difference
in Rich's blade.

11:26.603 --> 11:29.604
Winning this competition
is very important to me.

11:29.648 --> 11:31.189
I would like to expand
my shop

11:31.233 --> 11:33.692
and make it larger and easier
to work in.

11:33.735 --> 11:35.360
(Wil)
He can pull this off.

11:35.404 --> 11:37.028
(David)
With a beard like that,
all things are possible.

11:37.072 --> 11:38.196
Yes.

11:38.240 --> 11:39.322
(Wil)
30 minutes!

11:39.366 --> 11:42.742
You have 30 minutes remaining!

11:42.786 --> 11:44.244
♪ ♪

11:44.287 --> 11:46.371
So it looks like Joe
has ground a tip

11:46.415 --> 11:47.664
back into that blade.

11:47.708 --> 11:48.998
(J.)
Yeah, and it took him, what,

11:49.042 --> 11:50.500
about a total of 6, 7 minutes?

11:50.544 --> 11:52.001
I think I was able to recover.

11:52.045 --> 11:53.586
I not only have a reformed tip,

11:53.630 --> 11:55.714
but I still have a blade
that's lengthy enough,

11:55.757 --> 11:58.007
and I may actually be able
to move forward.

11:58.051 --> 11:59.843
It's how you react
to situations.

11:59.886 --> 12:01.386
(David)
I don't know how you react.

12:01.430 --> 12:03.096
I usually throw the blade
across the room.

12:03.140 --> 12:04.764
Yeah, and if it doesn't
break again,

12:04.808 --> 12:05.849
then it's okay.

12:05.892 --> 12:08.017
♪ ♪

12:08.061 --> 12:12.230
The serrated edge part
is throwing me out of whack.

12:12.274 --> 12:15.316
I didn't get my serrated edges
deep enough,

12:15.360 --> 12:19.070
and I washed 'em out
in the grinding process.

12:19.114 --> 12:20.947
I guess, as I'm watching--

12:20.991 --> 12:23.450
as I'm watching 'em
beating--bang on their--

12:23.493 --> 12:26.077
every dog has its day,
and this ain't mine.

12:26.121 --> 12:27.370
(Wil)
30 seconds!

12:27.414 --> 12:29.164
30 seconds remaining!

12:29.207 --> 12:35.044
♪ ♪

12:35.088 --> 12:36.838
10, 9,

12:36.882 --> 12:38.965
8, 7,

12:39.009 --> 12:41.009
6, 5,

12:41.052 --> 12:42.510
4, 3,

12:42.554 --> 12:44.721
2, 1.

12:44.765 --> 12:46.598
Set 'em down, gentlemen!

12:46.641 --> 12:48.141
Time is up!

12:48.185 --> 12:49.642
- Wow.
- Unreal.

12:49.686 --> 12:50.894
(J.)
I know; we can all
take a breath.

12:50.937 --> 12:53.188
(David)
Yeah.

12:53.231 --> 12:55.940
(Joe)
At this point, I don't know
if my blade

12:55.984 --> 12:57.984
is good enough to continue
in the competition,

12:58.028 --> 13:00.195
but I've already been through
the worst-case scenario.

13:00.238 --> 13:02.238
Nothing worse than what has
already happened to me

13:02.282 --> 13:03.990
can happen to me at this point.

13:04.034 --> 13:06.242
It can happen again, but that
could only be as bad

13:06.286 --> 13:07.869
as what's already happened.

13:07.913 --> 13:09.454
♪ ♪

13:09.498 --> 13:12.582
Your challenge was to forge
a 9-to-11-inch blade

13:12.626 --> 13:14.375
out of a bar
of high-carbon steel.

13:14.419 --> 13:18.087
The blade must have at least
4 inches of serrations.

13:18.131 --> 13:21.257
Now it's time for the judges
to take a look at your work.

13:21.301 --> 13:25.011
Joe, please present your weapon
to the judges.

13:25.055 --> 13:30.016
♪ ♪

13:30.060 --> 13:33.520
Good job on sucking it up
and reworking it.

13:33.563 --> 13:36.689
But the obvious question is
the tip issue you had.

13:36.733 --> 13:38.525
You lost about an inch
of that tip.

13:38.568 --> 13:41.110
How do you feel about the rework
that you did?

13:41.154 --> 13:42.487
(Joe)
I'm not necessarily pleased

13:42.531 --> 13:44.113
with the way the tip structure
is now

13:44.157 --> 13:46.282
versus the way it was initially.

13:46.326 --> 13:48.701
I think it's functional.

13:48.745 --> 13:50.119
Yeah.

13:50.163 --> 13:51.329
When that tip came off
and you decided

13:51.373 --> 13:53.122
to finish what you started

13:53.166 --> 13:56.292
is even more telling of what
a master bladesmith does.

13:56.336 --> 13:59.295
You adapted, you improvised,
and you overcame.

13:59.339 --> 14:02.006
It's still a functional weapon.

14:02.050 --> 14:04.884
But is it the best weapon?
That remains to be seen.

14:04.928 --> 14:06.135
But thank you
for not giving up.

14:06.179 --> 14:07.554
Thank you.

14:07.597 --> 14:09.222
Rich,
you're up next.

14:09.266 --> 14:13.810
♪ ♪

14:13.854 --> 14:16.312
It's definitely a beefy blade,

14:16.356 --> 14:18.815
and it's definitely got
the scare factor.

14:18.859 --> 14:22.026
I'm curious to see how well
it performs.

14:22.070 --> 14:24.153
(David)
As you were grinding away,
and we're going,

14:24.197 --> 14:26.906
"He's got nothing.
He's got no serrations."

14:26.950 --> 14:28.491
A minute later, you're like...
[imitates grinding]

14:28.535 --> 14:31.703
Which actually is kind of
a neat look.

14:31.746 --> 14:33.538
(Wil)
Matt, it's your turn.

14:33.582 --> 14:37.458
♪ ♪

14:37.502 --> 14:39.878
Well, I really love what you did
with the serration.

14:39.921 --> 14:43.006
You took a lot of time just
laying that in nice and slow,

14:43.049 --> 14:44.841
and so it's got
a really clean look.

14:44.885 --> 14:46.175
Thank you.

14:46.219 --> 14:47.510
You did stretch it out
quite a bit,

14:47.554 --> 14:49.512
and your tip is a lot more
tapered

14:49.556 --> 14:51.014
than your original drawing.

14:51.057 --> 14:52.348
How do you think that's gonna
hold up?

14:52.392 --> 14:54.017
I think this will be all right.

14:54.060 --> 14:55.518
Leaving myself just a little bit
short on material,

14:55.562 --> 14:57.353
and I wanted to make sure
I had the length.

14:57.397 --> 14:58.688
It's always a fine line.

14:58.732 --> 15:00.023
It's a very fine line.

15:00.066 --> 15:01.816
(Wil)
Billy, you're last up.

15:01.860 --> 15:05.361
♪ ♪

15:05.405 --> 15:07.947
I like the overall design
of the knife.

15:07.991 --> 15:10.074
It's a good point,
good profile.

15:10.118 --> 15:11.743
You also got hung up
on the serrations.

15:11.786 --> 15:14.537
Actually, what I did was,
on the grinder,

15:14.581 --> 15:16.539
I dug in too deep on one side,

15:16.583 --> 15:17.707
and I had to work on that.

15:17.751 --> 15:19.208
Okay.

15:19.252 --> 15:20.877
(Doug)
I like the design.

15:20.921 --> 15:23.421
Did you measure the
length of this serration?

15:23.465 --> 15:25.048
I did.

15:25.091 --> 15:27.467
4 1/8 is what I came up with.

15:30.096 --> 15:31.137
Thank you.

15:31.181 --> 15:33.181
♪ ♪

15:33.224 --> 15:35.433
Obviously, the judges
have much to discuss.

15:35.477 --> 15:38.561
They'll need some time to make
their decision.

15:38.605 --> 15:39.520
Thank you.

15:39.564 --> 15:47.779
♪ ♪

15:47.822 --> 15:50.657
Wow.

15:50.700 --> 15:51.783
That was rough.

15:51.826 --> 15:53.785
(Wil)
We have a lot to discuss.

15:53.828 --> 15:56.579
I hope they don't chop a finger
off in there or something.

15:56.623 --> 15:58.748
(Wil)
Let's start with Matt's blade.

15:58.792 --> 16:00.375
(J.)
I mean, he seemed like
he knew what he's doing.

16:00.418 --> 16:02.251
He gave us a clean blade.

16:02.295 --> 16:04.587
It's a little thin
on the tip to thrust.

16:04.631 --> 16:06.130
(David)
And it's nicely done
for handwork

16:06.174 --> 16:07.966
on a three-hour job.

16:08.009 --> 16:10.468
Let's take a look
at Rich's zombie killer.

16:10.512 --> 16:12.804
(David)
You know, if he had
designed this and said,

16:12.847 --> 16:15.932
"I'm going to make the most
badass post-apocalyptic

16:15.976 --> 16:17.976
zombie killing machine
I ever could,"

16:18.019 --> 16:19.811
I mean, he's almost right there.

16:19.854 --> 16:21.270
But it wasn't what he was
shooting for.

16:21.314 --> 16:22.772
He was shooting for more
of a classic Tanto

16:22.816 --> 16:25.441
with a large blade
and a long handle.

16:25.485 --> 16:27.110
Beauty is in the eye
of beholder.

16:27.153 --> 16:28.820
In terms of calling it crude,

16:28.863 --> 16:30.989
once again,
let's see the function.

16:31.032 --> 16:35.284
Worst-case scenario, you could
beat somebody to death with it.

16:35.328 --> 16:36.953
Let's look at Joe's blade.

16:36.997 --> 16:39.789
(David)
He broke a tip off,
and he reground.

16:39.833 --> 16:41.749
He gets credit for that.

16:41.793 --> 16:43.960
But...

16:44.004 --> 16:47.046
you got multiple fractures
up the tip.

16:47.090 --> 16:50.675
I'm counting two, three,
four, five.

16:50.719 --> 16:52.969
We've already seen that tip
break once,

16:53.013 --> 16:55.471
so we know how brittle
this tip is.

16:55.515 --> 16:57.849
Let's go ahead
and measure Joe's blade.

16:57.892 --> 17:00.143
The overall length of the blade
is...

17:00.186 --> 17:02.812
just shy of 9 1/2 inches,

17:02.856 --> 17:06.190
and the length of his
serrations...

17:06.234 --> 17:08.651
Yeah, by 1/8th of an inch,
he's under.

17:08.695 --> 17:11.320
That is unfortunate.

17:11.364 --> 17:13.156
Let's take a look
at Billy's blade.

17:13.199 --> 17:15.950
(J.)
Well, again, I like Billy's
overall profile.

17:15.994 --> 17:17.160
(David)
Can we get a measurement?

17:17.203 --> 17:19.746
So on the serrations,
we have...

17:19.789 --> 17:22.457
Wow.
Oh, he's way short.

17:22.500 --> 17:24.000
He's almost 1/2 inch
under.

17:24.044 --> 17:26.002
(J.)
We got more cracks too.

17:26.046 --> 17:29.005
There is one, two, three
big cracks.

17:29.049 --> 17:32.341
(Wil)
So we've got two guys
who didn't meet the specs

17:32.385 --> 17:33.885
for the length of the serration,

17:33.928 --> 17:35.845
but we can only remove
one of them this round.

17:35.889 --> 17:37.638
So it all comes down to quality.

17:37.682 --> 17:39.932
Have we made our decision?

17:39.976 --> 17:41.601
Yeah.
Yes, we have.

17:41.644 --> 17:43.186
- Yeah.
- We're all in agreement?

17:43.229 --> 17:44.520
- I think so.
- All in agreement.

17:44.564 --> 17:46.939
Okay, let's go tell
our bladesmiths.

17:46.983 --> 17:51.778
♪ ♪

17:51.821 --> 17:53.529
(Billy)
I'm freaking out.

17:53.573 --> 17:55.073
I have a big possible mistake.

17:55.116 --> 17:56.741
I may be going home today.

17:56.785 --> 18:00.203
(Joe)
I know my blade's not up to par.

18:00.246 --> 18:01.621
My only hope at this point is,

18:01.664 --> 18:03.581
somebody made a worse blade
than I did.

18:03.625 --> 18:06.584
[tense music]

18:06.628 --> 18:07.919
♪ ♪

18:07.962 --> 18:10.129
(Wil)
Gentlemen, the judges

18:10.173 --> 18:12.090
have made their decision.

18:12.133 --> 18:16.552
♪ ♪

18:16.596 --> 18:19.806
All of your blades
made the size parameters

18:19.849 --> 18:21.224
for this challenge.

18:21.267 --> 18:23.559
However, two of your blades

18:23.603 --> 18:27.897
did not meet the required
length of serration.

18:27.941 --> 18:30.233
Rich...

18:30.276 --> 18:32.110
Matt...

18:32.153 --> 18:33.236
you are safe.

18:33.279 --> 18:34.195
Well done.

18:34.239 --> 18:37.115
Billy...
and Joe,

18:37.158 --> 18:39.367
one of you
will be going home.

18:39.410 --> 18:41.702
The judges have made
their decision.

18:41.746 --> 18:47.083
♪ ♪

18:47.127 --> 18:49.252
Joe...

18:49.295 --> 18:50.670
you did not make the cut.

18:50.713 --> 18:52.255
(J.)
Well, Joe,

18:52.298 --> 18:53.840
we had a few different issues
to work with.

18:53.883 --> 18:56.425
You were 1/8th of an inch short
on those serrations.

18:56.469 --> 18:59.178
And, actually, if you
had had one more serration,

18:59.222 --> 19:01.305
you'd have made the parameters
we asked for.

19:01.349 --> 19:03.307
Also, when we saw
the tip break,

19:03.351 --> 19:04.934
we also saw the grain structure.

19:04.978 --> 19:06.144
It was very coarse

19:06.187 --> 19:08.104
from overheating in the forge.

19:08.148 --> 19:10.773
And we saw the lines
from the stress fractures

19:10.817 --> 19:12.275
up on the blade.

19:12.318 --> 19:14.652
I don't think that tip
would hold up.

19:14.696 --> 19:16.445
(Wil)
Joe?

19:16.489 --> 19:17.947
Please surrender your weapon.

19:17.991 --> 19:19.991
[light music]

19:20.034 --> 19:22.118
(Joe)
I overheated my steel,

19:22.162 --> 19:23.995
and there's no excuses for that.

19:24.038 --> 19:25.496
Right now, I wish I'd have been
a bit more cautious

19:25.540 --> 19:26.789
with my temperatures.

19:26.833 --> 19:28.124
I did well with the forging.

19:28.168 --> 19:29.792
I did well with the design,
I believe.

19:29.836 --> 19:31.961
It's just what should have been
my strengths,

19:32.005 --> 19:33.546
I allowed to become
my weaknesses.

19:33.590 --> 19:35.298
♪ ♪

19:35.341 --> 19:36.966
[tense music]

19:37.010 --> 19:39.510
Gentlemen, you've made it
through to round two.

19:39.554 --> 19:40.845
Your second challenge

19:40.889 --> 19:42.180
is to turn your blades

19:42.223 --> 19:44.140
into fully functioning weapons.

19:44.184 --> 19:45.808
There are three hours
on the clock.

19:45.852 --> 19:47.810
You must design and fabricate
a handle

19:47.854 --> 19:49.812
from the materials provided
for you.

19:49.856 --> 19:51.522
You can use that time to do

19:51.566 --> 19:54.817
any further work on your blade
if you feel the need.

19:54.861 --> 19:57.153
When the time runs out,

19:57.197 --> 20:00.323
your blades will be tested
for strength and durability

20:00.366 --> 20:02.658
and also their ability
to hold an edge

20:02.702 --> 20:05.494
in a specially designed
sharpness test.

20:05.538 --> 20:09.081
Only two of you will move
forward to the final.

20:09.125 --> 20:11.334
Your time starts...
now.

20:11.377 --> 20:13.002
(Matt)
Oh, yeah.

20:13.046 --> 20:14.337
I run over
to the handle materials,

20:14.380 --> 20:15.880
and I start looking
for something

20:15.924 --> 20:17.173
that's hefty enough
for a knife this size,

20:17.217 --> 20:18.758
antler or bone,

20:18.801 --> 20:20.885
something that I can use
the natural material

20:20.929 --> 20:22.553
as the finish,

20:22.597 --> 20:24.055
'cause if I have to start
polishing out a handle,

20:24.098 --> 20:25.181
I'm never gonna make the time.

20:25.225 --> 20:26.849
God, that is an awful sound.

20:26.893 --> 20:28.684
Antler is really strong,
but the pith,

20:28.728 --> 20:30.895
where the blood flows
through it, is very weak,

20:30.939 --> 20:32.438
and you just need to remove
all of it.

20:32.482 --> 20:35.149
I think this deer had
a calcium deficiency.

20:35.193 --> 20:36.943
So I drill out as much
as I possibly can,

20:36.986 --> 20:38.778
and then I fit that handle
through the tang.

20:38.821 --> 20:40.696
I have a hidden tang knife.

20:40.740 --> 20:43.449
This is the classic system
of how swords were assembled

20:43.493 --> 20:46.035
all the way through
medieval era.

20:46.079 --> 20:48.579
(Billy)
That's a bad deal right there.

20:48.623 --> 20:51.582
I chose to go with some
micarta handle material,

20:51.626 --> 20:53.376
and it looks a little bit sexy,
if I don't say.

20:53.419 --> 20:54.877
Wham.

20:54.921 --> 20:56.379
Now I need to think about

20:56.422 --> 20:58.297
how I'm gonna attach
my handle to the knife.

20:58.341 --> 21:00.174
Or I can use bolts
and I can drill

21:00.218 --> 21:02.802
appropriate-size holes
for these to fit in.

21:02.845 --> 21:04.553
Hope my dentist don't see that
in my mouth.

21:04.597 --> 21:06.138
And they actually screw together

21:06.182 --> 21:09.517
and put complete tension
on the knife handle itself.

21:09.560 --> 21:12.895
Now I'm cleaning up all
the epoxy that smooshed out

21:12.939 --> 21:14.689
whenever I glued
the handle on.

21:16.985 --> 21:18.067
That kind of bothers me.

21:18.111 --> 21:19.902
Ooh, doggies.

21:19.946 --> 21:21.570
(David)
What I'd like to see

21:21.614 --> 21:23.572
is Billy work on a blade
that's got a crack on it.

21:23.616 --> 21:24.949
(Wil)
Those flaws in his blade
are fixable,

21:24.993 --> 21:27.159
but he's wasting time.

21:27.203 --> 21:30.579
It's almost like Billy worked
on his handle as a distraction.

21:30.623 --> 21:33.124
You know, "I don't know exactly
what to do about this crack,

21:33.167 --> 21:35.334
but in the meantime,
I'm gonna make a handle."

21:35.378 --> 21:37.670
(J.)
We're only a half hour
into this.

21:37.714 --> 21:40.923
(Wil)
It could be the most beautiful
handle ever created...

21:40.967 --> 21:43.259
With the shortest,
squared-off, broken blade.

21:43.303 --> 21:48.806
♪

21:48.850 --> 21:58.899
♪ ♪

21:58.901 --> 22:03.946
♪ ♪

22:03.990 --> 22:05.614
I have a lot of pins.

22:05.658 --> 22:07.241
Any more pins,
we could go bowling.

22:07.285 --> 22:12.621
♪ ♪

22:12.665 --> 22:14.707
(J.)
Uh-oh. Oh!

22:14.751 --> 22:15.791
That didn't work very well.

22:15.835 --> 22:16.834
(J.)
That was Matt

22:16.878 --> 22:17.918
with the rotary tool.

22:17.962 --> 22:19.420
My weakest part is finish.

22:19.464 --> 22:20.671
Oh, that's not helpful.

22:20.715 --> 22:22.715
It just takes me a long time.

22:22.759 --> 22:23.966
So now I'm starting to panic
a little bit.

22:24.010 --> 22:25.634
- Sorry.
- No, go.

22:25.678 --> 22:27.136
I'm trying to rush too much,

22:27.180 --> 22:28.179
and I'm gonna break
what I'm doing.

22:28.222 --> 22:30.181
I need to stop panicking.

22:30.224 --> 22:31.724
Oh, come on.

22:31.768 --> 22:34.310
Sometimes bad stuff just happens
in knife making.

22:34.354 --> 22:36.312
- You doing all right, Matt?
- I hate these belts.

22:36.356 --> 22:37.813
(Wil)
The clock's really starting
to get to Matt.

22:37.857 --> 22:39.690
(Matt)
I kind of put myself behind.

22:39.734 --> 22:41.859
I'm not sure I'm gonna be able
to put this together.

22:49.619 --> 22:50.993
♪ ♪

22:51.037 --> 22:52.661
(J.)
Uh-oh. Oh!

22:52.705 --> 22:54.413
Three hours is tight.

22:54.457 --> 22:55.664
I'm trying to rush too much.

22:55.708 --> 22:57.458
Oh, come on.

22:57.502 --> 22:59.585
I need to stop panicking.

22:59.629 --> 23:01.670
You have one hour remaining.

23:01.714 --> 23:03.047
Put your respirators on.

23:03.091 --> 23:04.715
Time's rattling away,

23:04.759 --> 23:07.218
because I was concentrating
on a handle so bad,

23:07.261 --> 23:09.387
I forgot I had time
to work on the blade.

23:09.430 --> 23:12.223
All right, here's the money shot
where I stab myself.

23:12.266 --> 23:15.434
[rock music]

23:15.478 --> 23:16.852
(J.)
I'm glad to see that he did

23:16.896 --> 23:19.605
a bunch of blade work on that,
did clean it up.

23:19.649 --> 23:20.856
How are you, man?

23:20.900 --> 23:22.191
You know what?
I'm hanging in there.

23:22.235 --> 23:23.234
How about yourself?

23:23.277 --> 23:24.860
I think I'm doing well.

23:24.904 --> 23:26.195
I'll find out in a little bit.

23:26.239 --> 23:28.239
Looking sweet, buddy.

23:28.282 --> 23:29.407
There's 21 minutes left
on the clock,

23:29.450 --> 23:30.783
and they're chitchatting.

23:30.827 --> 23:32.576
(Billy)
I'm gonna do hand sanding

23:32.620 --> 23:34.870
and try to get some of the
rough grinds out of the blade.

23:34.914 --> 23:36.497
(David)
I think he's finally
on that blade.

23:36.541 --> 23:38.290
[tense music]

23:38.334 --> 23:40.668
(Wil)
I think we need to watch Billy
very closely

23:40.711 --> 23:42.044
for the next few minutes,

23:42.088 --> 23:43.337
because what he does here,

23:43.381 --> 23:45.548
it's gonna be critical.

23:45.591 --> 23:48.676
(David)
I'm hoping he doesn't crack it
off right there in the vise.

23:48.719 --> 23:51.303
(Billy)
You think you could get me
a Band-Aid? Thank you.

23:51.347 --> 23:53.389
In the knife shop,
you're always getting cut.

23:53.433 --> 23:54.890
The best thing's
a little Band-Aid.

23:54.934 --> 23:57.059
You put it on there, blow on it,
hold it,

23:57.103 --> 23:58.144
and you're ready to go again.

23:58.187 --> 24:01.730
(Wil)
10! 9! 8!

24:01.774 --> 24:04.733
7! 6! 5!

24:04.777 --> 24:07.611
4! 3! 2!

24:07.655 --> 24:08.737
1!

24:08.781 --> 24:10.072
Time's up, gentlemen.

24:10.116 --> 24:11.449
Time's up.

24:11.492 --> 24:13.284
Get it off.

24:13.327 --> 24:15.786
(Billy)
I've done all I can
with the blade.

24:15.830 --> 24:17.329
The handle looks really good.

24:17.373 --> 24:18.956
Going to see what they say.

24:19.000 --> 24:20.958
♪ ♪

24:21.002 --> 24:23.586
(Wil)
You've all made
some handsome blades,

24:23.629 --> 24:25.921
but can they cut it
in the testing arena?

24:25.965 --> 24:27.631
It's time to find out.

24:27.675 --> 24:29.633
J. will be testing
your blades' strength

24:29.677 --> 24:32.511
and durability
against these steel drums,

24:32.555 --> 24:34.430
followed by
a sharpness test

24:34.474 --> 24:35.973
against these ropes.

24:36.017 --> 24:38.601
♪ ♪

24:38.644 --> 24:40.311
Fellow bladesmiths,

24:40.354 --> 24:42.521
I'm gonna take
each of your blades,

24:42.565 --> 24:43.981
and I'm going to take
three attempts

24:44.025 --> 24:48.819
to pierce the steel
up to your serrations.

24:48.863 --> 24:50.821
Rich, you're going
to be first.

24:50.865 --> 24:59.914
♪ ♪

24:59.957 --> 25:02.208
[grunts]

25:02.251 --> 25:05.794
♪ ♪

25:05.838 --> 25:09.757
We do have a few issues
with the edge.

25:09.800 --> 25:13.093
There's a small crack
up here towards the tip,

25:13.137 --> 25:15.095
and we've got a flake
down towards the bottom.

25:15.139 --> 25:17.097
(Rich)
That's a devastating blow.

25:17.141 --> 25:19.975
I have no idea if I'm gonna
get through that sharpness test

25:20.019 --> 25:23.020
with chips in the blade.

25:23.064 --> 25:24.647
That's a thick-ass rope.

25:24.690 --> 25:27.483
We're gonna do three cuts
on each rope.

25:27.527 --> 25:28.984
I'm ready.

25:29.028 --> 25:37.868
♪ ♪

25:37.912 --> 25:40.371
With every slice,
I'm just hoping

25:40.414 --> 25:42.081
it's going to make it
through that rope.

25:42.124 --> 25:44.041
And if not,
that could be the end.

25:44.085 --> 25:47.545
[suspenseful music]

25:47.588 --> 25:49.755
[sighs]
[bleep].

25:49.799 --> 25:51.507
Had I given it more thought,

25:51.551 --> 25:53.509
I probably would have changed
the geometry of the blade

25:53.553 --> 25:56.345
to make it cut that rope easier.

25:57.640 --> 25:59.557
(J.)
Totally different blade, Matt.

25:59.600 --> 26:00.558
Are you ready?

26:00.601 --> 26:01.642
Try to break it.

26:01.686 --> 26:05.854
♪ ♪

26:05.898 --> 26:06.939
[grunts]

26:11.737 --> 26:12.695
Really?

26:12.738 --> 26:14.863
You are kidding me.

26:14.907 --> 26:16.782
I rode that thinness down
to the point

26:16.826 --> 26:18.742
where I thought it was just
gonna go right through.

26:18.786 --> 26:20.578
It just went in, like,
a half an inch.

26:20.621 --> 26:21.662
I'm shocked.

26:21.706 --> 26:24.665
[tense music]

26:24.709 --> 26:31.046
♪ ♪

26:31.090 --> 26:33.716
A thin blade should go through
with less pressure.

26:33.759 --> 26:35.301
I don't understand why
it didn't go through.

26:35.344 --> 26:36.802
So close.

26:36.846 --> 26:39.096
(J.)
Billy.

26:39.140 --> 26:41.765
I think you've known
from challenge one

26:41.809 --> 26:43.392
we've had a bit of an issue
with this blade.

26:43.436 --> 26:44.727
A big issue.

26:44.770 --> 26:46.562
(J.)
We've got three stress fractures

26:46.606 --> 26:48.314
at the serrations.

26:48.357 --> 26:49.773
Yes.

26:49.817 --> 26:50.899
(J.)
For safety reasons,

26:50.943 --> 26:52.568
I really don't feel comfortable

26:52.612 --> 26:54.570
thrusting this
into a steel drum.

26:55.865 --> 26:57.823
What the [bleep]?

26:57.867 --> 26:59.783
He's not gonna do
the thrust test.

26:59.827 --> 27:00.868
I'm screwed.

27:00.911 --> 27:03.287
[tense music]

27:11.130 --> 27:12.421
(J.)
Billy.

27:12.465 --> 27:15.799
We've got
three stress fractures.

27:15.843 --> 27:17.301
I really don't feel comfortable

27:17.345 --> 27:19.386
thrusting this
into a steel drum.

27:20.931 --> 27:22.598
(Billy)
He's not gonna do
the thrust test.

27:22.642 --> 27:24.558
What the Sam Heck am I gonna do?

27:24.602 --> 27:28.270
(J.)
Though you did give us
a finished and sharp knife,

27:28.314 --> 27:31.649
so I would like still
to do the sharpness test.

27:31.692 --> 27:33.442
(Billy)
I'm really thrilled

27:33.486 --> 27:35.778
that J.'s gonna do the cutting
part of the competition.

27:35.821 --> 27:38.947
I really want to see how my
blade cuts through that rope.

27:38.991 --> 27:41.950
[suspenseful music]

27:41.994 --> 27:50.000
♪ ♪

27:54.173 --> 27:56.340
Well, Billy, it did
pretty well on the rope.

27:56.384 --> 27:58.133
Got almost all the way through.

27:58.177 --> 28:00.344
It performed well.
Thank you.

28:00.388 --> 28:02.721
(Billy)
Even though the flaws
are in my blade,

28:02.765 --> 28:05.391
my knife did really well
on the cutting competition.

28:05.434 --> 28:08.560
Who knows? I may still have
a chance at this.

28:08.604 --> 28:11.563
[dramatic music]

28:11.607 --> 28:13.315
♪ ♪

28:13.359 --> 28:14.858
(Wil)
Gentlemen.

28:14.902 --> 28:16.068
The judges have made
their decision.

28:16.112 --> 28:18.654
♪ ♪

28:18.698 --> 28:19.988
Billy,

28:20.032 --> 28:21.657
you didn't make the cut.

28:21.701 --> 28:24.159
(David)
We all loved your handle,

28:24.203 --> 28:27.496
and you put a lot of time
in detailing a blade

28:27.540 --> 28:28.914
that had some real problems
to it.

28:28.958 --> 28:30.374
We all just kind of wish

28:30.418 --> 28:32.167
you had addressed
those fractures

28:32.211 --> 28:33.669
and given your blade

28:33.713 --> 28:35.379
a chance to be put through
the punch test.

28:35.423 --> 28:37.506
So, unfortunately,
we have to let you go.

28:37.550 --> 28:38.549
(Wil)
Billy?

28:38.592 --> 28:40.342
Please surrender your weapon.

28:40.386 --> 28:42.344
(Billy)
I'm feeling
a little disappointed

28:42.388 --> 28:43.595
that I didn't get to move on

28:43.639 --> 28:45.347
to the next part
of this competition.

28:45.391 --> 28:46.390
Thank you, gentlemen.

28:46.434 --> 28:47.516
Appreciate it.

28:47.560 --> 28:49.226
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

28:49.270 --> 28:51.061
(Billy)
Do I wish
I could have won this thing?

28:51.105 --> 28:52.855
Absolutely.

28:52.898 --> 28:54.398
♪ ♪

28:54.442 --> 28:58.360
[suspenseful music]

28:58.404 --> 29:01.613
Rich, Matt, you've made it
to the<i> Forged in Fire</i> final.

29:01.657 --> 29:03.031
So far,

29:03.075 --> 29:05.033
we've asked you to design
and produce

29:05.077 --> 29:07.494
a weapon of your own choosing.

29:07.538 --> 29:09.538
To claim
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> crown,

29:09.582 --> 29:12.624
you must design and forge
our mystery weapon,

29:12.668 --> 29:14.752
one of the most famous
and revered weapons

29:14.795 --> 29:16.670
from history.

29:16.714 --> 29:19.423
♪ ♪

29:19.467 --> 29:21.258
The Japanese katana.

29:21.302 --> 29:25.137
The katana is the traditional
weapon of the samurai,

29:25.181 --> 29:27.222
the noble class of warriors
in feudal Japan

29:27.266 --> 29:29.767
since around 800 A.D.

29:29.810 --> 29:32.060
The katana was formed
from hundreds of thin layers

29:32.104 --> 29:34.062
of the purest steel available.

29:34.106 --> 29:36.774
The quicker draw of the sword
was well suited to combat

29:36.817 --> 29:38.400
where life versus death

29:38.444 --> 29:40.611
depended on the weapon
you carried into battle.

29:40.654 --> 29:42.070
Over the centuries,

29:42.114 --> 29:43.906
the katana has taken on
many mythical properties

29:43.949 --> 29:45.574
in legend and culture,

29:45.618 --> 29:47.117
from an ability
to slice through other swords

29:47.161 --> 29:48.827
to splitting a hair.

29:48.871 --> 29:50.746
And it is the sword of choice
for characters

29:50.790 --> 29:53.540
in megahits like<i> Kill Bill</i>
and<i> The Walking Dead.</i>

29:53.584 --> 29:55.417
You must create

29:55.461 --> 29:58.754
an authentic, fully functioning
version of that weapon.

29:58.798 --> 30:01.089
(Matt)
I have mad respect to the guys
who make those things.

30:01.133 --> 30:04.259
A katana is so just...
[sighs] not my thing.

30:04.303 --> 30:06.470
(Rich)
The challenge of making a katana

30:06.514 --> 30:08.472
leveled the playing field
a little bit,

30:08.516 --> 30:10.849
because it was more in my style.

30:10.893 --> 30:13.685
(Wil)
You have five days
to complete this challenge.

30:13.729 --> 30:16.688
And just to give you
the best possible chance,

30:16.732 --> 30:18.774
we're sending you back
to your home forges

30:18.818 --> 30:21.443
for the final round.

30:21.487 --> 30:23.779
After the five days,
you will come back

30:23.823 --> 30:25.948
and present your sword
to the judges.

30:25.991 --> 30:27.157
They will put it
through a series

30:27.201 --> 30:30.285
of high-impact,
high-velocity tests.

30:30.329 --> 30:31.870
Once those tests
are completed,

30:31.914 --> 30:34.122
they will decide
who will be crowned

30:34.166 --> 30:37.459
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion

30:37.503 --> 30:41.046
and walk away with a check
for $10,000.

30:41.090 --> 30:43.131
Nice.

30:43.175 --> 30:44.299
Good luck, gentlemen.

30:44.343 --> 30:45.592
We'll see you in five days.

30:45.636 --> 30:48.303
♪ ♪

30:48.347 --> 30:51.265
[rock music]

30:51.308 --> 30:54.726
♪ ♪

30:54.770 --> 30:58.146
(Rich)
I am absolutely amazed
that I made it this far.

30:58.190 --> 31:00.148
At every stage
of the competition,

31:00.192 --> 31:02.901
I thought, "This is it.
I'm going home."

31:02.945 --> 31:06.488
With five days, I think
I can actually prove my worth.

31:06.532 --> 31:07.823
♪ ♪

31:07.867 --> 31:09.491
The next five days, for me,

31:09.535 --> 31:10.826
are going to be
a little more stressful

31:10.870 --> 31:12.327
than for Matt.

31:12.371 --> 31:15.873
I've got no power hammers,
no presses.

31:15.916 --> 31:17.624
Everything is by hand.

31:17.668 --> 31:22.212
[dramatic music]

31:22.256 --> 31:23.881
(Matt)
The competition was hard,

31:23.924 --> 31:25.674
but I did a good job,
and I went through,

31:25.718 --> 31:27.467
and I'd like to win
10 grand now.

31:27.511 --> 31:29.344
That'd be nice.

31:29.388 --> 31:32.014
I'm gonna go for
a full-hardened blade,

31:32.057 --> 31:34.266
so strong and so fine-grained,

31:34.310 --> 31:35.601
it should outperform
anything else

31:35.644 --> 31:36.935
that anybody can put
on the table.

31:36.979 --> 31:39.021
♪ ♪

31:39.064 --> 31:42.608
(Rich)
My goal is to get the blade
to where I can quench it.

31:42.651 --> 31:44.526
So what I'm doing here is,

31:44.570 --> 31:46.820
I'm breaking
all the sharp edges,

31:46.864 --> 31:48.864
because if you got
any sharp edges,

31:48.908 --> 31:52.492
you got a lot better chance
of cracking something.

31:52.536 --> 31:54.786
♪ ♪

31:54.830 --> 31:57.539
During the quenching process,
what will happen is,

31:57.583 --> 31:59.416
the molecules
in the edge of the blade

31:59.460 --> 32:03.378
will tighten up, and I'll get
a curve to the blade.

32:03.422 --> 32:05.464
And that's very important
to the process

32:05.507 --> 32:06.882
in this particular sword.

32:06.926 --> 32:08.383
This is where it all happens.

32:08.427 --> 32:10.594
It'll kill me, or it'll make me.

32:10.638 --> 32:13.305
Here we go.

32:13.349 --> 32:14.806
[whooshing noise]

32:14.850 --> 32:15.933
[crackling noise]

32:15.976 --> 32:18.602
[bleep] you.

32:18.646 --> 32:21.063
About four seconds
into the quench,

32:21.106 --> 32:22.648
I heard a loud tick.

32:22.691 --> 32:24.066
[cracking noise]

32:24.109 --> 32:27.069
I knew that was it
and it was all over.

32:27.112 --> 32:29.404
Several cracks along the tip.

32:29.448 --> 32:33.575
I just got the blade way too hot
before I quenched it,

32:33.619 --> 32:35.285
and when you've got
too hot a blade

32:35.329 --> 32:36.912
and you throw it
in cooler water,

32:36.956 --> 32:38.455
then it's a crack.

32:38.499 --> 32:41.583
I'm not gonna say all is lost
just yet.

32:41.627 --> 32:44.127
With only having two days,
it's gonna be tough.

32:44.171 --> 32:46.088
I'm gonna get to work.

32:46.131 --> 32:48.590
[dramatic music]

32:48.634 --> 32:50.592
♪ ♪

32:50.636 --> 32:52.427
That's ready for heat treating.

32:52.471 --> 32:54.930
I'm gonna slide my blade
down there.

32:54.974 --> 32:57.391
About 600 degrees.

32:57.434 --> 33:00.060
I'm just gonna bring it up
and let it cool.

33:00.104 --> 33:03.355
♪ ♪

33:03.399 --> 33:04.940
I'm doing this for my son.

33:04.984 --> 33:06.274
I'm doing this so that
he can be proud of me.

33:06.318 --> 33:07.693
See what Daddy's doing?

33:07.736 --> 33:08.986
Setting the stone right now.

33:09.029 --> 33:11.989
♪ ♪

33:12.032 --> 33:13.323
Nice.

33:13.367 --> 33:14.825
I like this sword a lot.

33:14.868 --> 33:16.493
I'm still a little apprehensive

33:16.537 --> 33:18.787
about what the judges
are going to be looking for.

33:18.831 --> 33:20.288
I'm just going to cut
a couple water bottles

33:20.332 --> 33:21.873
to make sure
the geometry is good.

33:21.917 --> 33:25.168
♪ ♪

33:25.212 --> 33:27.629
That was a successful test cut.

33:27.673 --> 33:30.590
This is a really good sword.

33:30.634 --> 33:34.678
♪ ♪

33:34.722 --> 33:36.304
[tense music]

33:36.348 --> 33:37.472
(Rich)
I got one day to go,

33:37.516 --> 33:39.307
so I'm gonna bust my ass,

33:39.351 --> 33:40.892
and I'm gonna try
and get something made

33:40.936 --> 33:43.270
that I'm proud of.

33:43.313 --> 33:46.523
This is my final shot
to stay in the competition.

33:46.567 --> 33:49.651
If this blade doesn't survive,
I'm out.

33:49.695 --> 33:52.320
I'm getting ready.

33:52.364 --> 33:53.905
I'm quenching now.

33:53.949 --> 33:57.951
♪ ♪

34:05.586 --> 34:08.003
♪ ♪

34:08.047 --> 34:10.005
(Wil)
Gentlemen,

34:10.049 --> 34:11.548
I hope that your time at home

34:11.592 --> 34:13.550
was productive
and inspired.

34:13.594 --> 34:17.387
Matt, can you tell us
a little bit about the process?

34:17.431 --> 34:20.724
(Matt)
I decided to go for
a performance blade,

34:20.768 --> 34:22.642
so I did a pretty good
heat treat on it,

34:22.686 --> 34:25.729
and then I did leather risers
and a leather wrap over the top.

34:25.773 --> 34:28.023
It's a fairly traditional
European design,

34:28.067 --> 34:29.733
but I have seen similar wraps

34:29.777 --> 34:31.443
on katana.

34:31.487 --> 34:33.195
It's not the fanciest sword
I've ever made,

34:33.238 --> 34:35.447
but I'm very proud of the sword.

34:35.491 --> 34:37.199
(Wil)
Rich, what was your thinking

34:37.242 --> 34:39.034
beside the design in this sword?

34:39.078 --> 34:42.537
(Rich)
I went with a modern-style
full-tang handle,

34:42.581 --> 34:45.540
which is not traditional
in a katana.

34:45.584 --> 34:46.708
I actually had a little bit
of a problem

34:46.752 --> 34:48.877
about three days in

34:48.921 --> 34:51.129
and had to make
an entirely new blade,

34:51.173 --> 34:53.882
so I was backed off
by about a day.

34:53.926 --> 34:57.219
With that said, in the end,
it all came out all right.

34:57.262 --> 34:58.720
(Wil)
Great.

34:58.764 --> 35:01.640
To measure how your blades
stand up against flesh,

35:01.683 --> 35:03.391
Doug will cut through
these fish

35:03.435 --> 35:04.810
that are suspended

35:04.853 --> 35:07.938
in a multiple-target
engagement pattern.

35:07.981 --> 35:10.232
Making sushi.

35:10.275 --> 35:12.025
[dramatic music]

35:12.069 --> 35:13.568
(Doug)
Rich, yours is up.

35:13.612 --> 35:14.945
Let's put it to the test.

35:14.988 --> 35:22.994
♪ ♪

35:33.048 --> 35:34.923
Nice.

35:34.967 --> 35:36.383
It will cut.

35:36.426 --> 35:37.425
Yes, it will.

35:37.469 --> 35:40.929
It felt good in the slice.

35:40.973 --> 35:43.056
But the recovery was
a little heavier,

35:43.100 --> 35:46.268
but it still felt like
it'll give me a close shave.

35:46.311 --> 35:47.644
Good job.

35:47.688 --> 35:50.272
Okay, Matt, you're up next.
Are you ready?

35:50.315 --> 35:51.523
Yup.

35:51.567 --> 35:54.526
[dramatic music]

35:54.570 --> 36:02.576
♪ ♪

36:05.455 --> 36:08.290
It doesn't cut, and I'm
a little confused by that.

36:08.333 --> 36:09.624
I don't know why it didn't cut.

36:09.668 --> 36:15.463
♪ ♪

36:15.507 --> 36:17.465
[laughs]

36:17.509 --> 36:19.634
It's got a very good feel to it.

36:19.678 --> 36:20.927
It's very light.

36:20.971 --> 36:22.929
It's got a very nice
balance to it.

36:22.973 --> 36:25.640
And...

36:25.684 --> 36:26.725
it'll cut.

36:26.768 --> 36:27.976
[laughs]

36:28.020 --> 36:29.686
Now for the kill test.

36:29.730 --> 36:31.813
In this, we have
a ballistics dummy

36:31.857 --> 36:34.482
that pretty much simulates
the human form,

36:34.526 --> 36:35.984
organs and tissues.

36:36.028 --> 36:39.237
The katana traditionally has
a razor-sharp edge.

36:39.281 --> 36:43.658
That allows me to find the gaps
in between the armor.

36:43.702 --> 36:44.993
I'm going to try that
with your blades

36:45.037 --> 36:46.328
to see how well it does.

36:46.371 --> 36:48.538
Rich, you're up first.

36:48.582 --> 36:56.588
♪ ♪

37:09.019 --> 37:10.352
[sword tings]

37:10.395 --> 37:12.604
Let's take a look
at the damage.

37:12.648 --> 37:14.022
♪ ♪

37:14.066 --> 37:15.232
Oh.

37:15.275 --> 37:17.359
The thrust and the slice

37:17.402 --> 37:20.654
went all the way into
the internal organs in here.

37:20.697 --> 37:25.659
And the kill shot went deep
all the way into the liver.

37:25.702 --> 37:28.745
I think, on the kill test,

37:28.789 --> 37:29.871
this will kill.

37:29.915 --> 37:32.749
Okay, Matt, you're up.

37:32.793 --> 37:35.752
[dramatic music]

37:35.796 --> 37:43.802
♪ ♪

37:50.644 --> 37:52.811
[sword tings]

37:52.854 --> 37:57.107
♪ ♪

37:57.150 --> 37:58.775
Definitely through
the laceration,

37:58.819 --> 38:00.819
he's disemboweled here.

38:00.862 --> 38:03.530
A nice big puncture in here.

38:03.573 --> 38:04.990
That definitely will get
the liver.

38:05.033 --> 38:06.741
♪ ♪

38:06.785 --> 38:08.743
I think it's passed
the kill test.

38:08.787 --> 38:10.203
Thank you.

38:10.247 --> 38:13.081
You both obviously brought
deadly implements

38:13.125 --> 38:14.833
of war here.

38:14.876 --> 38:18.086
But now it's time
to lock and load, gentlemen,

38:18.130 --> 38:19.754
because for the strength test,

38:19.798 --> 38:21.172
we're leaving the Forge

38:21.216 --> 38:23.550
and we're heading
to the gun range.

38:23.593 --> 38:24.968
What?

38:25.012 --> 38:27.053
♪ ♪

38:33.562 --> 38:38.606
♪ ♪

38:38.650 --> 38:40.317
(Wil)
All right, gentlemen.

38:40.360 --> 38:42.319
This is the final test

38:42.362 --> 38:44.446
for the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
championship.

38:44.489 --> 38:45.989
It's the strength test.

38:46.033 --> 38:47.907
Your weapons
will be tested

38:47.951 --> 38:51.077
on their ability
to split a bullet.

38:51.121 --> 38:54.372
Your swords are gonna be
locked into a vise.

38:54.416 --> 38:56.791
Then we're gonna fire a bullet
at your blade.

38:56.835 --> 38:59.252
Don't bring a sword
to a gunfight.

38:59.296 --> 39:01.880
All I can think of
in my head is,

39:01.923 --> 39:05.008
"You're about to destroy
two beautiful swords."

39:05.052 --> 39:08.219
[rock music]

39:08.263 --> 39:09.471
All right, Matt.

39:09.514 --> 39:10.722
You ready?

39:10.766 --> 39:12.474
Break it.

39:12.517 --> 39:15.143
♪ ♪

39:15.187 --> 39:17.979
3, 2, 1.

39:18.023 --> 39:19.230
Engage.

39:19.274 --> 39:20.231
[gunshot]

39:20.275 --> 39:21.232
- Oh!
- Yes!

39:21.276 --> 39:23.318
- Yes.
- Nice.

39:23.362 --> 39:25.362
[gunshot]

39:25.405 --> 39:27.155
(Matt voice-over)
The gun fires,

39:27.199 --> 39:29.240
and it breaks the bullet
in three pieces.

39:29.284 --> 39:30.533
I don't even think
the sword moved.

39:30.577 --> 39:32.494
It just--pfft!

39:32.537 --> 39:36.206
Well, Matt, your sword
split a bullet.

39:36.249 --> 39:37.957
There's no damage on the edge
at all.

39:38.001 --> 39:39.667
Held up extremely well.

39:39.711 --> 39:42.879
That is a real, true sign
of your craftsmanship.

39:42.923 --> 39:44.506
- Thank you.
- Very well done.

39:44.549 --> 39:46.007
All right, Rich, you're up next.

39:46.051 --> 39:47.675
(Rich voice-over)
When I look at them

39:47.719 --> 39:50.345
set the gun up and get ready
to shoot that blade,

39:50.389 --> 39:52.847
there's a little bit of doubt
in the back of my mind

39:52.891 --> 39:55.308
thinking, "It may not
survive this."

39:55.352 --> 39:56.476
♪ ♪

39:56.520 --> 40:00.355
(Wil)
3, 2, 1, engage.

40:00.399 --> 40:01.398
[gunshot]

40:01.441 --> 40:02.774
- Nice!
- Oh, yeah!

40:02.818 --> 40:04.692
- Sweet.
- Ha ha!

40:04.736 --> 40:06.528
[gunshot]

40:06.571 --> 40:08.655
- Wow.
- Definitely got a split there.

40:08.698 --> 40:10.240
- Nice.
- Yeah, that's a split.

40:10.283 --> 40:12.200
- I like it.
- That blade didn't even move.

40:12.244 --> 40:14.369
(Rich)
It splits the bullet.

40:14.413 --> 40:16.413
I couldn't have been happier.

40:16.456 --> 40:19.040
My blade held up against Matt's

40:19.084 --> 40:21.209
in every way, shape, or form.

40:21.253 --> 40:23.044
There's no mark on the blade
at all.

40:23.088 --> 40:24.712
Held up perfectly.

40:24.756 --> 40:27.715
No chipping.
Everything looks great.

40:27.759 --> 40:29.300
Thank you.

40:29.344 --> 40:30.885
Congratulations, gentlemen.

40:30.929 --> 40:32.929
You should be proud
of the work that you've done,

40:32.973 --> 40:34.931
which only makes
the judges' decision

40:34.975 --> 40:36.224
that much harder.

40:36.268 --> 40:37.725
We'll see you back at the Forge.

40:37.769 --> 40:40.061
(Matt)
Both of us passed everything.

40:40.105 --> 40:43.231
Our swords performed
like they're supposed to,

40:43.275 --> 40:45.233
and it's up to the judges.

40:45.277 --> 40:47.735
(Rich)
I think the judges have
a very tough decision to make.

40:47.779 --> 40:57.787
♪ ♪

41:00.625 --> 41:01.749
Matt, Rich...

41:01.793 --> 41:04.210
♪ ♪

41:04.254 --> 41:06.629
In just five days,
you have both forged elegant

41:06.673 --> 41:09.090
and lethal
Japanese katanas.

41:09.134 --> 41:10.800
But in this competition,

41:10.844 --> 41:14.220
there can only be one winner
of $10,000.

41:14.264 --> 41:15.847
J.?

41:15.891 --> 41:17.265
Well, Matt, your sword blade
performed beautifully.

41:17.309 --> 41:18.433
It split the bullet
into three pieces,

41:18.477 --> 41:19.934
and we know

41:19.978 --> 41:21.478
it was still even sharp
where the bullet hit it.

41:21.521 --> 41:22.729
That was a great job.

41:22.772 --> 41:24.731
The concern I had, though,

41:24.774 --> 41:26.357
is with the samurai armor,

41:26.401 --> 41:28.401
it did not pierce nearly as much
as I thought it would.

41:28.445 --> 41:29.777
I think there's a little bit
of drag on the blade,

41:29.821 --> 41:30.945
which concerns me,

41:30.989 --> 41:32.572
towards the tip there.

41:32.616 --> 41:33.781
Comments for Rich?

41:33.825 --> 41:35.450
(Doug)
Rich, on the fish cut,

41:35.494 --> 41:36.993
it did quite well.

41:37.037 --> 41:39.162
It is top-heavy,
so it'll slice through.

41:39.206 --> 41:41.122
But then I had to pull back
for recovery

41:41.166 --> 41:42.874
and had to use my other hand.

41:42.918 --> 41:44.959
But I needed it
for recovery also.

41:45.003 --> 41:47.545
(J.)
The creativity
of your handle set-up

41:47.589 --> 41:49.130
was really nice,

41:49.174 --> 41:50.798
but I have some issues
with the construction,

41:50.842 --> 41:52.550
you know, the pins being
a little too close to the edge.

41:52.594 --> 41:53.885
That's something
that concerns me.

41:53.929 --> 41:55.220
♪ ♪

41:55.263 --> 41:56.304
Unfortunately,

41:56.348 --> 41:57.805
in this competition,

41:57.849 --> 42:00.058
there can only be one winner.

42:00.101 --> 42:03.478
♪ ♪

42:03.522 --> 42:04.562
Matthew.

42:04.606 --> 42:06.981
♪ ♪

42:07.025 --> 42:09.526
You are the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion.

42:09.569 --> 42:10.818
Congratulations.

42:10.862 --> 42:13.196
[rock music]

42:13.240 --> 42:15.490
Rich, you did not make the cut.

42:15.534 --> 42:18.368
(David)
I wish you had done
a little bit more finish work.

42:18.411 --> 42:20.495
You let the handle get
a little bit skinny,

42:20.539 --> 42:24.165
and it was almost the same
proportions on each side, so...

42:24.209 --> 42:26.209
I know you ran
into a time constraint,

42:26.253 --> 42:28.044
but it did split a bullet,

42:28.088 --> 42:29.837
and that's truly
something to be proud of.

42:29.881 --> 42:31.881
(Rich)
I feel a little disappointed,

42:31.925 --> 42:33.633
but the better bladesmith won.

42:33.677 --> 42:35.343
♪ ♪

42:35.387 --> 42:38.179
(Wil)
Well, Matt, congratulations.

42:38.223 --> 42:39.847
You are the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion.

42:39.891 --> 42:41.683
You're gonna claim
a $10,000 check.

42:41.726 --> 42:43.142
How do you feel?

42:43.186 --> 42:44.394
This is awesome.

42:44.437 --> 42:46.354
Your blade is beautiful.

42:46.398 --> 42:48.356
Not only is it beautiful,
but it's fast.

42:48.400 --> 42:50.191
It cut so cleanly
through the fish.

42:50.235 --> 42:51.693
And on the ballistic dummies,

42:51.736 --> 42:53.194
that just disemboweled it
for the kill test.

42:53.238 --> 42:54.404
Great job.

42:54.447 --> 42:55.863
Blade aside,

42:55.907 --> 42:57.156
I was really impressed
with your handle setup.

42:57.200 --> 42:58.575
Symmetrically,
it was correct.

42:58.618 --> 43:00.451
We could get good control,
good grip on it.

43:00.495 --> 43:01.869
Very nicely done.

43:01.913 --> 43:03.705
(Matt)
This is such a rush.

43:03.748 --> 43:05.873
I want to drive home
and kiss my son.

43:05.917 --> 43:07.625
I am the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion.

43:07.669 --> 43:10.420
♪ ♪
